      <section*|Geometric Interpretation of <math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u> for <math|2\<times\>2> Matrices><label|geometric-interpretation-of-u-1-v-u-for-2-times-2-matrices>

      <subsection*|Conjugation as Change of Basis><label|conjugation-as-change-of-basis>

      The expression <math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u> represents conjugation of the matrix <math|v> by the invertible matrix <math|u>. Geometrically, this corresponds to applying a change of coordinates.\ 

      <subsection*|Linear Transformation Interpretation><label|linear-transformation-interpretation>

      If we interpret <math|v> as representing a linear transformation in some coordinate system, then <math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u> represents the same transformation but expressed in a different coordinate system, where <math|u> provides the change of basis.\ 

      <subsection*|Special Cases><label|special-cases>

      <subsubsection*|Rotation Matrices><label|rotation-matrices>

      When <math|u> and <math|v> are rotation matrices in <math|\<bbb-R\><rsup|2>>, the conjugation <math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u> represents composing rotations: first rotate by angle <math|\<theta\><rsub|u>> (via <math|u>), then apply rotation <math|v>, then undo the initial rotation.\ 

      <subsubsection*|Scaling and Shearing><label|scaling-and-shearing>

      \;

      For diagonal matrices representing scaling, conjugation can transform scaling directions. For shear matrices, conjugation can rotate the direction of shearing.\ 

      <subsection*|Geometric Invariants><label|geometric-invariants>

      The conjugation preserves several geometric properties:\ 

      <\itemize>
        <item>Determinant: <math|det <around|(|u<rsup|-1>*v*u|)>=det <around|(|v|)>>

        <item>Trace: <math|<math-up|tr><around|(|u<rsup|-1>*v*u|)>=<math-up|tr><around|(|v|)>>

        <item>Eigenvalues (and thus the type of transformation: rotation, scaling, etc.)
      </itemize>

      <subsection*|Coordinate Transformation><label|coordinate-transformation>

      If <math|v> transforms vectors as <math|w=v*x>, then in the coordinate system transformed by <math|u>, the same transformation appears as <math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u>. This is the geometric essence of similarity transformations in linear algebra.\ 
