      <section*|Non-Commutativity of 3D Rotations and Conjugation><label|non-commutativity-of-3d-rotations-and-conjugation>

      <subsection*|Fundamental Difference from 2D><label|fundamental-difference-from-2d>

      In 3D space, rotation matrices do <with|font-series|bold|not> commute, making the geometric interpretation of <math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u> much richer and more complex than in 2D.\ 

      <subsection*|Geometric Interpretation in 3D><label|geometric-interpretation-in-3d>

      <subsubsection*|Step-by-Step Transformation><label|step-by-step-transformation>

      For a vector <math|x\<in\>\<bbb-R\><rsup|3>>, the transformation <math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u*x> proceeds as:\ 

      <\enumerate>
        <assign|labelenumi|<macro|<number|<enumi-nr>|arabic>.>>

        <item><with|font-series|bold|mode|math|u*x>: Rotate <math|x> by rotation <math|u> in the original coordinate system

        <item><with|font-series|bold|mode|math|v*<around|(|u*x|)>>: Apply rotation <math|v> to the result

        <item><with|font-series|bold|mode|math|u<rsup|-1>*<around|(|v*u*x|)>>: Apply the inverse of rotation <math|u>
      </enumerate>

      <subsubsection*|Key Geometric Insight><label|key-geometric-insight>

      The conjugation <math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u> represents applying rotation <math|v> <with|font-series|bold|in the coordinate system that has been rotated by <math|u>>.\ 

      <subsection*|Concrete Example><label|concrete-example>

      Let <math|v> be a rotation about the z-axis, and <math|u> be a rotation about the x-axis:\ 

      <\equation*>
        v=R<rsub|z><around|(|\<theta\>|)>,<space|1em>u=R<rsub|x><around|(|\<phi\>|)>
      </equation*>

      Then <math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u=R<rsub|x>*<around|(|-\<phi\>|)>*R<rsub|z><around|(|\<theta\>|)>*R<rsub|x><around|(|\<phi\>|)>> represents:\ 

      <\itemize>
        <item>A rotation about the z-axis <with|font-series|bold|after the coordinate system has been tilted by rotation <math|u>>

        <item>This is equivalent to rotating about a <with|font-series|bold|different axis> in the original coordinate system
      </itemize>

      <subsection*|Axis Transformation><label|axis-transformation>

      The most important geometric interpretation:\ 

      <with|font-series|bold|If <math|v> rotates about axis <math|<math-bf|a>> by angle <math|\<theta\>>, then <math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u> rotates about axis <math|u<rsup|-1><math-bf|a>> by the same angle <math|\<theta\>>.>\ 

      <subsubsection*|Mathematical Foundation><label|mathematical-foundation>

      This follows from the fact that for rotation matrices:\ 

      <\equation*>
        u<rsup|-1>*R<around|(|<math-bf|a>,\<theta\>|)>*u=R<around|(|u<rsup|-1><math-bf|a>,\<theta\>|)>
      </equation*>

      where <math|R<around|(|<math-bf|a>,\<theta\>|)>> denotes rotation about axis <math|<math-bf|a>> by angle <math|\<theta\>>.\ 

      <subsection*|Physical Interpretation><label|physical-interpretation>

      <subsubsection*|Changing Reference Frames><label|changing-reference-frames>

      Think of <math|u> as changing your viewpoint or coordinate system:\ 

      <\itemize>
        <item><with|font-series|bold|Original frame>: You see rotation <math|v> happening

        <item><with|font-series|bold|Transformed frame>: After applying <math|u>, you're in a new orientation

        <item><with|font-series|bold|In transformed frame>: You see what looks like rotation <math|v>

        <item><with|font-series|bold|Return to original>: When you apply <math|u<rsup|-1>>, you see the net effect
      </itemize>

      <subsubsection*|Everyday Analogy><label|everyday-analogy>

      If you:\ 

      <\enumerate>
        <assign|labelenumi|<macro|<number|<enumi-nr>|arabic>.>>

        <item>Turn your head (rotation <math|u>)

        <item>Watch someone spin an object (rotation <math|v>)

        <item>Turn your head back to original position (<math|u<rsup|-1>>)
      </enumerate>

      The object appears to have rotated about a different axis than if you had kept your head still.\ 

      <subsection*|Mathematical Consequences><label|mathematical-consequences>

      <subsubsection*|Non-Commutation Proof><label|non-commutation-proof>

      For <math|u=R<rsub|x><around|(|90<rsup|\<circ\>>|)>> and <math|v=R<rsub|y><around|(|90<rsup|\<circ\>>|)>>:\ 

      <\equation*>
        u<rsup|-1>*v*u\<neq\>v<rsup|-1>*u*v\<neq\>u*v
      </equation*>

      This demonstrates that the order matters fundamentally in 3D.\ 

      <subsubsection*|Eigenvalue Preservation><label|eigenvalue-preservation>

      While the rotation axis changes, the conjugation preserves:\ 

      <\itemize>
        <item>Rotation angle (modulo periodicity)

        <item>Determinant (<math|=1> for rotations)

        <item>Trace (related to rotation angle)
      </itemize>

      <subsection*|Summary><label|summary>

      The geometric meaning of <math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u> in 3D is: <with|font-series|bold|Take the rotation <math|v> and apply it in a coordinate system that has been transformed by <math|u>>. This changes the effective rotation axis while preserving the rotation angle, explaining why 3D rotations don't commute and demonstrating the rich structure of 3D rotational geometry.\ 
