      <subsection*|Conjugation as Change of Basis><label|conjugation-as-change-of-basis>

      The expression <math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u> represents conjugation of the matrix <math|v> by the invertible matrix <math|u>. Geometrically, this corresponds to applying a change of coordinates.\ 

      explain with examples
    <|unfolded-io-text>
      Of course. Let's break down the concept of conjugation as a change of basis with concrete examples.\ 

      <subsubsection*|The Core Idea><label|the-core-idea>

      Think of a matrix <math|v> as a set of instructions for a transformation (like rotation or scaling) <with|font-series|bold|in a specific language> (the standard coordinate system). The matrix <math|u> contains the dictionary to translate into a new language (a new coordinate system).\ 

      The operation <math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u> does the following:\ 

      <\enumerate>
        <assign|labelenumi|<macro|<number|<enumi-nr>|arabic>.>>

        <item><math|u>: <with|font-series|bold|Translate> a vector from the new language back to the standard language.

        <item><math|v>: <with|font-series|bold|Apply the transformation> in the standard language.

        <item><math|u<rsup|-1>>: <with|font-series|bold|Translate> the result back into the new language.
      </enumerate>

      The result is that <math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u> represents the <with|font-series|bold|same transformation> as <math|v>, but its instructions are now written in the “new language” defined by the basis given by <math|u>.\ 

      <hrule>

      <subsubsection*|Example 1: Scaling in a Rotated Frame><label|example-1-scaling-in-a-rotated-frame>

      Let's say <math|v> is a matrix that stretches space along the x-axis.\ 

      <\equation*>
        v=<matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|2>|<cell|0>>|<row|<cell|0>|<cell|1>>>>><space|1em><text|(Stretch by 2 in the x-direction)>
      </equation*>

      Now, let <math|u> be a <math|45<rsup|\<circ\>>> rotation matrix. Its columns form a new basis: the first basis vector points in the direction (1, 1) and the second in (-1, 1).\ 

      <\equation*>
        u=<matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|cos 45<rsup|\<circ\>>>|<cell|-sin 45<rsup|\<circ\>>>>|<row|<cell|sin 45<rsup|\<circ\>>>|<cell|cos 45<rsup|\<circ\>>>>>>>=<frac|1|<sqrt|2>><matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|-1>>|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|1>>>>>
      </equation*>

      The conjugate <math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u> tells us what the “x-axis scaling” transformation <math|v> looks like in this rotated coordinate system.\ 

      <\equation*>
        u<rsup|-1>*v*u=<frac|1|<sqrt|2>><matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|1>>|<row|<cell|-1>|<cell|1>>>>><matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|2>|<cell|0>>|<row|<cell|0>|<cell|1>>>>><frac|1|<sqrt|2>><matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|-1>>|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|1>>>>>=<frac|1|2><matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|3>|<cell|-1>>|<row|<cell|-1>|<cell|3>>>>>
      </equation*>

      <with|font-series|bold|Interpretation:>\ 

      <\itemize>
        <item><with|font-series|bold|Original <math|v>>: A pure scaling along the x-axis. It has a simple diagonal form.

        <item><with|font-series|bold|Conjugated <math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u>>: This is no longer a simple scaling. It's a transformation that stretches space along the direction (1, 1) and squishes it along the perpendicular direction (1, -1). Geometrically, it's the same action—stretching along the original x-axis—but <with|font-series|bold|described from the point of view of the rotated coordinate system>, it looks like a different kind of stretch.
      </itemize>

      <subsubsection*|Example 2: Reflection in a New Basis><label|example-2-reflection-in-a-new-basis>

      Let <math|v> be a reflection across the line <math|y=x>.\ 

      <\equation*>
        v=<matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|0>|<cell|1>>|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|0>>>>><space|1em><text|(Swap x and y coordinates)>
      </equation*>

      Now, let's choose a new basis <math|u> where the first basis vector is already on the line of reflection (1, 1) and the second is perpendicular to it (1, -1).\ 

      <\equation*>
        u=<matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|1>>|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|-1>>>>>
      </equation*>

      Let's compute the conjugate. First, find <math|u<rsup|-1>>:\ 

      <\equation*>
        u<rsup|-1>=<frac|1|-2><matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|-1>|<cell|-1>>|<row|<cell|-1>|<cell|1>>>>>=<frac|1|2><matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|1>>|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|-1>>>>>
      </equation*>

      Now compute <math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u>:\ 

      <\equation*>
        u<rsup|-1>*v*u=<frac|1|2><matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|1>>|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|-1>>>>><matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|0>|<cell|1>>|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|0>>>>><matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|1>>|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|-1>>>>>
      </equation*>

      First, <math|v*u>:\ 

      <\equation*>
        v*u=<matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|0>|<cell|1>>|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|0>>>>><matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|1>>|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|-1>>>>>=<matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|-1>>|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|1>>>>>
      </equation*>

      Now, <math|u<rsup|-1>*<around|(|v*u|)>>:\ 

      <\equation*>
        u<rsup|-1>*<around|(|v*u|)>=<frac|1|2><matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|1>>|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|-1>>>>><matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|-1>>|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|1>>>>>=<frac|1|2><matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|2>|<cell|0>>|<row|<cell|0>|<cell|-2>>>>>=<matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|0>>|<row|<cell|0>|<cell|-1>>>>>
      </equation*>

      <with|font-series|bold|Interpretation:>\ 

      <\itemize>
        <item><with|font-series|bold|Original <math|v>>: A reflection that swaps coordinates. Its matrix is not diagonal.

        <item><with|font-series|bold|Conjugated <math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u>>: In the new, “natural” basis <math|u>, the reflection simply becomes <math|<matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|0>>|<row|<cell|0>|<cell|-1>>>>>>. This is a <with|font-series|bold|pure reflection> across the first basis vector. It leaves the first coordinate unchanged and flips the sign of the second coordinate. The transformation is the same, but in this well-chosen basis, its description becomes dramatically simpler.
      </itemize>

      <subsubsection*|Summary><label|summary>

      <tabular|<tformat|<twith|table-hmode|min>|<twith|table-width|1par>|<cwith|1|-1|1|-1|cell-hyphen|t>|<table|<row|<cell|Step in ( u^{-1} v u )>|<cell|Geometric Action>|<cell|“Language” Analogy>>|<row|<cell|( u )>|<cell|Takes a vector from the <strong|new basis> and expresses it in the <strong|standard basis>.>|<cell|Translate from “New Language” to “Standard Language”.>>|<row|<cell|( v )>|<cell|Performs the transformation in the <strong|standard basis>.>|<cell|Follow the instructions written in “Standard Language”.>>|<row|<cell|( u^{-1} )>|<cell|Takes the result back to the <strong|new basis>.>|<cell|Translate the result back into “New Language”.>>>>>

      The power of conjugation is that it allows us to understand a complex-looking transformation by finding a basis (<math|u>) in which its description (<math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u>) becomes simple (often diagonal). This is the fundamental idea behind diagonalization and many other techniques in linear algebra.\ 
    </unfolded-io-text>

