      Similarly, how to interp <math|u v u<rsup|-1>>? compare with <math|u <rsup|-1>v u>.
    <|unfolded-io-text>
      Of course. This is an excellent question because it highlights a crucial subtlety in the geometric interpretation.\ 

      The expressions <math|u*v*u<rsup|-1>> and <math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u> are closely related, and the difference boils down to a single question: <with|font-series|bold|Are we transforming the object, or are we transforming the observer (the coordinate system)?>\ 

      Let's use the “language” analogy from before, where a matrix represents a transformation in a specific coordinate system.\ 

      <hrule>

      <subsubsection*|Interpretation of <math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u>: Transforming the Object><label|interpretation-of-u-1-v-u-transforming-the-object>

      This is the “<with|font-series|bold|alias>” interpretation (from the Latin for “other name”). Here, the <with|font-series|bold|vector gets a new name> (alias) in the original coordinate system.\ 

      <\enumerate>
        <assign|labelenumi|<macro|<number|<enumi-nr>|arabic>.>>

        <item><math|u>: Take a vector from the <with|font-series|bold|new coordinate system> and express its coordinates in the <with|font-series|bold|original system>.

        <item><math|v>: Apply the transformation <math|v> in the <with|font-series|bold|original coordinate system>.

        <item><math|u<rsup|-1>>: Take the result and express its coordinates back in the <with|font-series|bold|new system>.
      </enumerate>

      <with|font-series|bold|In short:> <math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u> is the transformation <math|v> <with|font-series|bold|as seen from the new coordinate system> defined by <math|u>. The object (the transformation <math|v>) is the same, but we are describing it using a different set of rulers and protractors (the new basis).\ 

      <with|font-series|bold|Analogy:> You have a recipe (transformation <math|v>) written in English (original basis). <math|u> is the French-to-English dictionary. <math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u> is the process of translating the recipe into French (new basis) so a French chef can follow it. The recipe itself (the transformation) hasn't changed.\ 

      <hrule>

      <subsubsection*|Interpretation of <math|u*v*u<rsup|-1>>: Transforming the Observer><label|interpretation-of-u-v-u-1-transforming-the-observer>

      This is the “<with|font-series|bold|alibi>” interpretation (from the Latin for “elsewhere”). Here, the <with|font-series|bold|vector is moved to a new place> (alibi).\ 

      <\enumerate>
        <assign|labelenumi|<macro|<number|<enumi-nr>|arabic>.>>

        <item><math|u<rsup|-1>>: Take a vector from the <with|font-series|bold|original coordinate system> and express its coordinates in the <with|font-series|bold|new system>.

        <item><math|v>: Apply the transformation <math|v> in the <with|font-series|bold|new coordinate system>.

        <item><math|u>: Take the result and express its coordinates back in the <with|font-series|bold|original system>.
      </enumerate>

      <with|font-series|bold|In short:> <math|u*v*u<rsup|-1>> is the transformation that <with|font-series|bold|acts like <math|v>, but in the new coordinate system>, and then we interpret the final result back in the original system. It's as if we've <em|moved the entire universe> by <math|u>, performed <math|v>, and then moved everything back.\ 

      <with|font-series|bold|Analogy:> You are standing still (original frame). You command someone: “First, rotate the entire room around me by <math|u<rsup|-1>> (so now <em|I> am in a new orientation relative to the room), now perform the spin <math|v>, and finally, rotate the entire room back to its original orientation (<math|u>).” The final position of the object is what <math|u*v*u<rsup|-1>> does.\ 

      <hrule>

      <subsubsection*|Direct Comparison with a Concrete Example><label|direct-comparison-with-a-concrete-example>

      Let's use the same scaling example from before.\ 

      <\itemize>
        <item><with|font-series|bold|Transformation <math|v>>: Scale by 2 along the x-axis.
      </itemize>

      <\equation*>
        v=<matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|2>|<cell|0>>|<row|<cell|0>|<cell|1>>>>>
      </equation*>

      <\itemize>
        <item><with|font-series|bold|Basis Change <math|u>>: A 45\<degree\> rotation.
      </itemize>

      <\equation*>
        u=<frac|1|<sqrt|2>><matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|-1>>|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|1>>>>>
      </equation*>

      We already computed:\ 

      <\equation*>
        u<rsup|-1>*v*u=<frac|1|2><matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|3>|<cell|-1>>|<row|<cell|-1>|<cell|3>>>>>
      </equation*>

      This is the scaling-by-2-along-x <with|font-series|bold|described in the rotated coordinate system>.\ 

      Now let's compute the other order:\ 

      <\equation*>
        u*v*u<rsup|-1>=<frac|1|<sqrt|2>><matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|-1>>|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|1>>>>><matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|2>|<cell|0>>|<row|<cell|0>|<cell|1>>>>><frac|1|<sqrt|2>><matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|1>>|<row|<cell|-1>|<cell|1>>>>>=<frac|1|2><matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|3>|<cell|1>>|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|3>>>>>
      </equation*>

      <with|font-series|bold|Geometric Interpretation:>\ 

      <\itemize>
        <item><math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u=<frac|1|2><matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|3>|<cell|-1>>|<row|<cell|-1>|<cell|3>>>>>>: This is a stretch along the original x-axis (direction (1,0)), but its matrix looks complicated because our “reporting” frame (the basis <math|u>) is tilted.

        <item><math|u*v*u<rsup|-1>=<frac|1|2><matrix|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|3>|<cell|1>>|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|3>>>>>>: This is a stretch along the <em|new> x-axis (the first column of <math|u>, which is direction (1,1)), described in the <em|original> coordinate system.
      </itemize>

