      <subsubsection*|Summary and Key Relationship><label|summary-and-key-relationship>

      The most concise way to relate them is this:\ 

      <with|font-series|bold|If <math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u> represents transformation <math|v> in the new coordinate system defined by <math|u>, then <math|u*v*u<rsup|-1>> represents the <em|inverse> of that idea.>\ 

      In fact, they are inverses of each other in a specific sense:\ 

      <\equation*>
        <around|(|u*v*u<rsup|-1>|)><rsup|-1>=u*v<rsup|-1>*u<rsup|-1>
      </equation*>

      But more intuitively, if you define <math|w=u<rsup|-1>*v*u>, then the “active” transformation that does the same physical action as <math|w> but in the original frame is <math|u*w*u<rsup|-1>=v>.\ 

      <with|font-series|bold|The takeaway:> They are two sides of the same coin. One describes how the same transformation appears from a different viewpoint (<math|u<rsup|-1>*v*u>), while the other uses a transformation to create a new, related transformation in the original viewpoint (<math|u*v*u<rsup|-1>>).\ 
